â€‹ðŸ“ˆ Analysis and Breakdowns
â€‹The project includes several visualizations breaking down attrition across different employee characteristics:  
â€‹Attrition by Department (Filter): The data is initially filtered by department, showing three main groups: Human Resources, Research & Development, and Sales.  
â€‹Attrition by Gender: Shows the count of male (150) versus female (87) employees who have left the company.  
â€‹Attrition by Education: Breaks down attrition based on education fields such as Life Sciences, Marketing, Medical, and Technical Degree.  
â€‹The largest percentages shown are 38% and 27% (Medical).  
â€‹Attrition by Age: Segments attrition into five age groups: 18-25, 26-35, 36-45, 46-55, and 55+.  
â€‹The 26-35 age group has the highest attrition count (44).  
â€‹Attrition by Salary Slab: Divides attrition counts into salary ranges (Upto 5k, 5k-10k, 10k-15k, 15k+).  
â€‹The 5k-10k slab has the highest count of attrition (163).  
â€‹Attrition by Job Role (Top 4): This visualization highlights the job roles with the highest number of attritions.  
â€‹The top job roles for attrition are Laboratory Technician (62), Sales Executive (57), Research Scientist (47), and Sales Representative (33).  
â€‹Attrition by Year at Company: Shows how attrition is distributed based on the number of years employees have been with the company.  
â€‹Job Satisfaction: This table shows the total count of attrition (237.0) broken down by Job Role and a Job Satisfaction rating (1, 2, 3, 4).  
â€‹The total attrition counts for several Job Roles are listed, such as Laboratory Technician (62.0), Sales Executive (57.0), and Research Scientist (47.0).  
